<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910219-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>910219-0048.</DOCID><HL>   Pima Sandamp;L Branches   To Reopen as Units   Of Bank of America</HL><DATE>02/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   BAC SCNC</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)SOUTHERN U.S. BANKS (BAS)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The 40 branches of Pima Federal Savings andamp;Loan Association, Tucson, Ariz., will reopen today as unitsof Bank of America Arizona, a subsidiary of BankAmericaCorp., the Resolution Trust Corp. said.   As part of a transaction announced Friday, Bank of Americais assuming all deposits and secured liabilities from PimaFederal, which had about $1.78 billion in assets. Bank ofAmerica agreed to pay the RTC a premium of $11.3 million toacquire the deposits and will buy about $1 billion of thefailed institution's assets.</LP><TEXT>   The RTC will provide a cash advance of about $701 millionto Bank of America, and will retain $783 million of Pima'sassets. The RTC plans to recover some of the advance byselling assets, and estimates that the transaction ultimatelywill cost the government $299 million.   The RTC also sold Security Federal Savings, Columbia,S.C., to South Carolina National Bank, a subsidiary of SouthCarolina National Corp., also of Columbia. The acquiring bankwill pay a $12 million premium, and will buy about $107.2million of assets. The RTC is advancing $445.6 million toSouth Carolina National, and puts the cost of the transactionat about $105.7 million, after asset sales.   In addition, the nine branches of Mid Kansas Savings andamp;Loan Association, Wichita, Kansas, were sold to fiveinstitutions in the state. Mid Kansas Savings had $435.9million of assets, and the five acquiring institutions paid atotal of $6.5 million in premiums. The RTC expects thesetransactions to ultimately cost the government $128.5million.</TEXT></DOC>